clusters.name: The CBD Core
clusters.corridors: Central transport hub with Flinders Street Station serving Frankston, Sandringham, and City Loop lines, and Southern Cross Station providing regional V/Line access. Metro Tunnel stations State Library and Town Hall serve the Sunbury, Cranbourne, and Pakenham lines. Melbourne Central Station connects the City Loop. Free Tram Zone covers the CBD with tram routes 1, 6, 16, 30, 35, 109 operating through Collins, Bourke, and Swanston Streets.

clusters.name: West Melbourne
clusters.corridors: Flagstaff Station on the City Loop provides rail access via Frankston, Craigieburn, and other loop services. Southern Cross Station is accessible via short walk. Tram 30 and 35 run through Spencer Street and King Street connecting to the broader Free Tram Zone and CBD.

clusters.name: Southbank-Port Melbourne Corridor
clusters.corridors: Tram-centric corridor with Route 109 serving Port Melbourne, Route 96 through South Melbourne, and Route 1 extending to South Melbourne Beach. City Road and Clarendon Street are key traffic corridors. Southern Cross Station is accessible via short tram connection.

clusters.name: South Wharf Precinct
clusters.corridors: Located near Southern Cross Station providing direct access to Sunbury, Werribee, and Williamstown lines via short walking distance. Tram routes operate along Clarendon Street with connections to the wider network. Citylink freeway provides vehicular connectivity to outer suburbs.

clusters.name: The Parkville-University Belt
clusters.corridors: Melbourne Central Station and nearby Flinders Street Station provide rail access to all Metro lines. Tram 19, 58, and 59 traverse Royal Parade and Flemington Road connecting the University of Melbourne precinct and Royal Melbourne Hospital. Direct proximity to the Free Tram Zone.

clusters.name: North Melbourne-Kensington Gateway
clusters.corridors: North Melbourne Station on the Craigieburn, Upfield, Werribee, and Williamstown lines provides multi-directional rail access. Kensington Station serves the Werribee and Williamstown lines. Tram 57, 58, and 59 run along Flemington Road and Macaulay Road.

clusters.name: The Fitzroy-Carlton Creative Belt
clusters.corridors: Tram 86 runs along Smith Street serving Fitzroy and Collingwood, while Tram 11 traverses Brunswick Street. Tram 96 extends along Nicholson Street. Lygon Street in Carlton is the main dining and shopping strip. Parliament Station and Collingwood Station provide nearest rail access.

clusters.name: The Northern Crest
clusters.corridors: Rushall Station on the Mernda Line provides rail access. Tram 96 runs along Nicholson Street and Tram 11 extends through Brunswick Street. Rathdowne Street is a key arterial connecting the precinct to Carlton and the CBD.

clusters.name: The Brunswick East Connection
clusters.corridors: Rushall Station on the Mernda Line provides rail interchange. Tram 96 traverses Nicholson Street connecting to the CBD. Lygon Street and St Georges Road are key traffic corridors. Merri Creek provides a green space and cycling corridor.

clusters.name: Northcote-Thornbury Corridor
clusters.corridors: Thornbury Station and Northcote Station both serve the Mernda Line providing direct rail access to the CBD. High Street Northcote is a major shopping and dining strip. Tram 86 operates along Plenty Road and St Georges Road provides secondary connectivity.

clusters.name: The Preston Hub
clusters.corridors: Preston Station and Bell Station on the Mernda Line provide rail access to the city. High Street Preston is a major shopping strip. Tram 86 operates along Plenty Road. Bell Street is a key east-west arterial.

clusters.name: The Brunswick-Coburg Spine
clusters.corridors: Brunswick Station and Coburg Station on the Upfield Line provide direct rail access to the CBD. Sydney Road features Tram 19 as the primary north-south corridor. Tram 58 operates along Melville Road. Bell Street provides east-west connectivity. Upfield bike path offers alternative transport.

clusters.name: East Melbourne Gateway
clusters.corridors: Collingwood Station serves the Mernda and Hurstbridge lines. Jolimont Station (Belgrave/Lilydale/Glen Waverley/Alamein lines) provides interchange access. Hoddle Street and Victoria Parade form key arterials. Tram 48 and 75 run along Wellington Parade.

clusters.name: The Richmond Hub
clusters.corridors: Richmond Station is a major interchange serving Alamein, Belgrave, Frankston, Glen Waverley, Lilydale, and Sandringham lines (Cranbourne/Pakenham now bypass via Metro Tunnel). Bridge Road, Swan Street, and Church Street are primary retail corridors. Tram 70 and 78 provide direct city connections.

clusters.name: Cremorne-Burnley Pocket
clusters.corridors: Burnley Station (Alamein/Belgrave/Glen Waverley/Lilydale lines) provides rail access. CityLink/Monash Freeway interchange provides east-west arterial access. Church Street and Swan Street extension form local corridors. Tram 70 extends through Cremorne.

clusters.name: Hawthorn Heritage Core
clusters.corridors: Hawthorn and Glenferrie stations (Belgrave/Lilydale/Alamein lines) serve this heritage precinct. Glenferrie Road is a major shopping strip. Tram 16 runs along Glenferrie Road and Tram 75 along Burwood Road toward the city.

clusters.name: Kew Riverside
clusters.corridors: Glenferrie Station (Belgrave/Lilydale/Alamein lines) provides primary rail access. Tram 16 runs along Glenferrie Road through Kew. High Street Kew and Cotham Road form heritage shopping strips. Studley Park and Yarra River corridor provide greenway links.

clusters.name: The Camberwell Junction
clusters.corridors: Camberwell Station (Alamein/Belgrave/Lilydale) and Canterbury Station (Belgrave/Lilydale) bracket this cluster. Camberwell Junction is a major shopping and transport hub. Burke Road and Riversdale Road form key retail arteries. Tram 72 and 75 intersect at the junction.

clusters.name: The Ashburton-Camberwell Heights
clusters.corridors: Camberwell Station (Alamein/Belgrave/Lilydale lines) provides major rail access. Ashburton Station (Alamein Line) serves the southern section. Tooronga Road and Burke Road are primary commercial corridors. Tram 72 terminates at Camberwell Junction.

clusters.name: Canterbury-Surrey Hills
clusters.corridors: Canterbury Station and Union Station (Belgrave/Lilydale lines) provide rail access. Union Road and Canterbury Road form the main corridors. Quiet residential area east of Camberwell.

clusters.name: The Balwyn Ridge
clusters.corridors: No direct rail. Tram 48 (via Doncaster Road) serves North Balwyn terminus. Whitehorse Road, Balwyn Road, and Belmore Road form main local corridors. Bus routes connect to Box Hill Station and the city via Eastern Freeway.

clusters.name: Kew East-Balwyn North
clusters.corridors: No direct rail. Tram 48 (Doncaster Road) provides main transit. Burke Road and Kilby Road form principal local arteries. Bus connections link to Kew Junction and Box Hill Station.

clusters.name: The Malvern-Glen Iris Ridge
clusters.corridors: Malvern Station (Frankston Line) and Glen Iris Station (Glen Waverley Line) provide rail access. Tram 5 runs along Wattletree Road and Tram 6 along High Street. Wattletree Road is a key commercial strip.

clusters.name: The South Yarra-Toorak Belt
clusters.corridors: South Yarra Station serves the Frankston and Sandringham lines (Cranbourne/Pakenham now bypass via Metro Tunnel). Toorak Station (Frankston Line) and Kooyong Station (Glen Waverley Line) provide additional rail access. Toorak Road, Chapel Street, and Tram 58 form the commercial spine.

clusters.name: The Chapel Street Spine
clusters.corridors: Windsor and Prahran stations (Sandringham Line) and Armadale Station (Frankston Line) provide direct CBD connections. Chapel Street is the main commercial strip through Prahran and Windsor. High Street Armadale provides major retail. Tram 6 (High St) and Tram 78 (Chapel St) complement rail.

clusters.name: The Kooyong-Malvern Corridor
clusters.corridors: Armadale Station and Malvern Station (Frankston Line) and Kooyong Station (Glen Waverley Line) form a triangle of rail access. Glenferrie Road and Wattletree Road are primary shopping strips. Tram 5 along Wattletree Road. Kooyong tennis precinct anchors the eastern edge.

clusters.name: Albert Park-Middle Park Bayside
clusters.corridors: Served by Tram 1 along the bay through South Melbourne Beach and Tram 96 heading to St Kilda. Beaconsfield Parade provides direct waterfront access. Albert Park Lake and Bridport Street shopping strip anchor the area. No direct rail — nearest South Yarra Station via connecting trams.

clusters.name: The St Kilda Foreshore
clusters.corridors: Tram 96 connects St Kilda Beach to East Brunswick via the foreshore. Tram 3 provides cross-suburb connections to East Malvern. No direct rail — Balaclava and Windsor stations nearest. Fitzroy Street, Acland Street, and The Esplanade form the entertainment and shopping core. Luna Park.

clusters.name: Balaclava-Ripponlea
clusters.corridors: Balaclava Station and Ripponlea Station on the Sandringham Line provide direct CBD access. Carlisle Street in Balaclava is a major shopping and dining strip. Hotham Street and Glen Eira Road provide additional retail. Tram 3 and 67 nearby.

clusters.name: The Ivanhoe Ridge
clusters.corridors: Eaglemont and Ivanhoe stations (Hurstbridge Line) provide direct rail to the city. Upper Heidelberg Road and The Boulevard form main corridors. Yarra River frontage. Ivanhoe village shopping strip is a local retail anchor.

clusters.name: The Fairfield-Alphington Bend
clusters.corridors: Fairfield and Alphington stations (Hurstbridge Line) serve this riverside precinct. Station Street Fairfield and Heidelberg Road form main retail strips. Yarra River bend through Fairfield Boathouse area. Near Darebin Creek confluence.

clusters.name: Heidelberg Hub
clusters.corridors: Heidelberg and Rosanna stations (Hurstbridge Line) provide rail access. Burgundy Street is a major shopping strip. Austin Hospital and Heidelberg Repatriation Hospital form significant employment anchors. Banksia Street and Lower Plenty Road connect to broader corridors.

clusters.name: The Viewbank-Rosanna Basin
clusters.corridors: Rosanna Station (Hurstbridge Line) provides primary rail access. Rosanna Road is the main arterial. Yarra Valley parklands and heritage reserves. Olympic Village heritage precinct in Heidelberg West. Bus connections serve La Trobe University campus.

clusters.name: The Bulleen Valley
clusters.corridors: No direct rail. Manningham Road and Thompsons Road form main arteries. Eastern Freeway provides express east-west access. Bulleen Park & Ride serves commuter connections. Bus routes connect via Eastern Freeway corridor to Doncaster and the city.

clusters.name: The Caulfield Interchange
clusters.corridors: Caulfield Station is a major interchange serving Frankston, Cranbourne, and Pakenham lines. Elsternwick Station (Sandringham Line) provides secondary rail access. Monash University Caulfield campus. Glen Huntly Road and Normanby Road are primary retail streets. Tram 3, 64, and 67.

clusters.name: Caulfield East-Malvern East Ridge
clusters.corridors: Caulfield Station (Frankston/Cranbourne/Pakenham lines) provides the primary rail hub. Dandenong Road and Waverley Road form main arteries. Monash Freeway provides rapid access to Clayton campus and outer suburbs. Bus connections to Monash University Clayton.

clusters.name: Glen Huntly-Carnegie Corridor
clusters.corridors: Glen Huntly Station (Frankston Line) and Carnegie Station (Pakenham/Cranbourne lines via Metro Tunnel) serve this corridor from two different rail lines. Glen Huntly Road is the primary shopping strip. Koornang Road Carnegie is a major food and multicultural dining precinct. Neerim Road provides secondary connectivity.

clusters.name: The Carnegie-Murrumbeena Pocket
clusters.corridors: Carnegie, Murrumbeena, and Hughesdale stations all serve the Cranbourne/Pakenham lines with elevated rail and level crossings removed. Koornang Road, Poath Road, and Neerim Road form a close-knit grid. Positioned on the Caulfield to Dandenong corridor.

clusters.name: The Oakleigh Hub
clusters.corridors: Oakleigh and Huntingdale stations serve the Cranbourne/Pakenham lines. Eaton Mall Oakleigh is the major Greek precinct and dining strip. Warrigal Road and Dandenong Road provide through-routes. Bus from Huntingdale Station to Monash University Clayton campus.

clusters.name: The Footscray Hub
clusters.corridors: Footscray Station is a major interchange serving the Sunbury Line (via Metro Tunnel), Werribee, and Williamstown lines. Seddon Station (Werribee/Williamstown lines). Leeds Street, Barkly Street, and Nicholson Street form the commercial core. Footscray Market and Hopkins Street dining precinct.

clusters.name: The Maribyrnong Bend
clusters.corridors: Tram 57 connects Maribyrnong to Flinders Street Station. Tram 82 extends through Moonee Ponds to Footscray. Ascot Vale Station (Craigieburn Line) is nearest rail. Highpoint Shopping Centre is the major retail anchor. Raleigh Road and Maribyrnong Road provide local connectivity.

clusters.name: Yarraville-Kingsville Village
clusters.corridors: Yarraville and Seddon stations (Werribee/Williamstown lines) provide regular CBD services. Anderson Street Yarraville is a charming village high street. Somerville Road and Williamstown Road provide residential connectivity. Quiet village character with low-rise development.

clusters.name: Spotswood-Newport Gateway
clusters.corridors: Spotswood and Newport stations serve the Werribee/Williamstown lines, with Newport as a junction station. Melbourne Road and Hudsons Road are primary corridors. The Strand Newport for waterfront dining. Scienceworks museum.

clusters.name: The Williamstown Peninsula
clusters.corridors: Newport, Williamstown, and Williamstown North stations all serve the Williamstown Line with direct CBD connections. Nelson Place waterfront dining strip. Ferguson Street historic main street. Williamstown Beach. Ferry from Gem Pier to the CBD.

clusters.name: The Altona Coastal Strip
clusters.corridors: Seaholme and Altona stations serve the Werribee Line with regular CBD services. Pier Street Altona. Millers Road and Kororoit Creek Road. Cherry Lake and Altona Beach foreshore provide major recreational amenity.

clusters.name: The Brooklyn-Tottenham Industrial Belt
clusters.corridors: Tottenham Station and West Footscray Station (Sunbury Line via Metro Tunnel). Geelong Road and Sunshine Road are major through-routes. Near Western Ring Road access. Mixed industrial and residential character.

clusters.name: The Sunshine Hub
clusters.corridors: Sunshine Station is a major interchange on the Sunbury Line (via Metro Tunnel) with V/Line connections to Bendigo and Ballarat. Ballarat Road and Hampshire Road form the primary shopping and commercial spine. Braybrook extends as a residential hinterland along Ballarat Road.

clusters.name: Avondale-Keilor East Heights
clusters.corridors: No direct rail. Bus routes along Keilor Road connect to Essendon Station (Craigieburn Line) and Watergardens Station (Sunbury Line). Military Road and Buckley Street are primary local routes. Calder Freeway and Western Ring Road access. Residential area with larger blocks.

clusters.name: Flemington-Ascot Vale Corridor
clusters.corridors: Flemington Bridge Station (Upfield Line) and Ascot Vale Station (Craigieburn Line) provide dual rail corridors. Mount Alexander Road and Epsom Road are primary streets. Flemington Racecourse. Tram 57 and 59 extend connectivity.

clusters.name: Moonee Ponds-Strathmore
clusters.corridors: Moonee Ponds and Strathmore stations serve the Craigieburn Line. Puckle Street Moonee Ponds is a major shopping strip. Tram 82 extends toward Footscray. Pascoe Vale Road and Mount Alexander Road provide connectivity.

clusters.name: The Essendon Corridor
clusters.corridors: Essendon and Strathmore stations serve the Craigieburn Line with direct CBD access. Rose Street Essendon is a village high street. Keilor Road and Buckley Street are primary corridors. Near Tullamarine Freeway for airport access.

clusters.name: Aberfeldie-Essendon West
clusters.corridors: Near Essendon and Moonee Ponds stations (Craigieburn Line). Buckley Street and Maribyrnong Road form main corridors. Maribyrnong River corridor provides open space. Predominantly family-oriented residential area.

clusters.name: Niddrie-Keilor East
clusters.corridors: No direct rail. Bus routes along Keilor Road connect to Essendon Station (Craigieburn) and Watergardens Station (Sunbury). Keilor Road and Milleara Road are primary routes. Niddrie shopping strip. Tullamarine Freeway access.

clusters.name: The Brighton Foreshore
clusters.corridors: Brighton Beach and Hampton stations serve the Sandringham Line with direct CBD and bayside connections. Church Street Brighton is a village shopping precinct. Hampton Street and Bay Street connect to Port Phillip Bay foreshore and iconic beach boxes.

clusters.name: Bentleigh-McKinnon Corridor
clusters.corridors: Bentleigh and McKinnon stations serve the Frankston Line with elevated rail and removed level crossings. Centre Road Bentleigh is the major shopping strip. East Boundary Road and Jasper Road provide secondary connectivity.

clusters.name: Gardenvale-Elsternwick
clusters.corridors: Gardenvale and Elsternwick stations serve the Sandringham Line. Glen Huntly Road extends through Elsternwick as a village high street. Nepean Highway provides through-traffic. Near Caulfield Racecourse.

clusters.name: Portsea & Sorrento
clusters.corridors: Bus route 788 (Frankston–Portsea via Dromana & Rosebud) serves this coastal strip. Point Nepean Road is the primary route. Mornington Peninsula National Park and historic Sorrento village provide key landmarks.

clusters.name: Rye & St Andrews Beach
clusters.corridors: Bus route 788 (Frankston–Portsea) passes through Rye with stops at Rye Shopping Centre. Point Nepean Road provides the main coastal corridor. Noted for surf beaches including Gunnamatta and St Andrews Beach.

clusters.name: Cape Schanck
clusters.corridors: Limited direct bus service; accessible via Point Nepean Road from Rye and Portsea. Cape Schanck is part of Mornington Peninsula National Park with walking tracks to Fingal Beach and Cape Schanck Boardwalk.

clusters.name: Rosebud & Capel Sound
clusters.corridors: Bus route 788 (Frankston–Portsea) serves Rosebud with multiple stops. Point Nepean Road and Nepean Highway provide key road access. Rosebud is a major regional hub with shopping and aquatic facilities.

clusters.name: Main Ridge & Boneo
clusters.corridors: Bus route 788 connects Rosebud; Main Ridge is primarily car-accessed via local roads. Known as wine country with scenic hinterland roads and the Red Hill Market.

clusters.name: Dromana & Arthurs Seat
clusters.corridors: Bus routes 788 (Frankston–Portsea) and 781 (Frankston–Dromana via Mount Eliza & Mornington) serve Dromana. Nepean Highway and Point Nepean Road are main routes. Arthurs Seat provides elevated views over Port Phillip Bay.

clusters.name: Red Hill
clusters.corridors: Limited direct bus service; primarily car-accessed from Mornington or Rosebud. Red Hill is renowned for wineries, galleries, and the Red Hill Market. Sandy Bay Road and local roads provide key access.

clusters.name: Mount Martha & Safety Beach
clusters.corridors: Bus routes 781 (Frankston–Dromana via Mount Eliza & Mornington) and 788 serve this corridor. Nepean Highway and Point Nepean Road provide main access. Mount Martha village shopping and beach amenities.

clusters.name: Merricks North
clusters.corridors: Limited public transport; car-accessed via local roads from Red Hill and Merricks. Noted for rural and wine country character with access to hinterland roads.

clusters.name: Moorooduc & Bittern
clusters.corridors: Moorooduc Highway provides the main east-west corridor linking to Frankston. Limited bus service; primarily car-accessed. Frankston-Flinders Road provides secondary connectivity.

clusters.name: Mornington & Mount Eliza
clusters.corridors: Bus routes 781 and 785 (Frankston–Mornington/Mount Eliza) and route 788 serve this hub. Mornington Peninsula Freeway (M11) provides major access north. Main Street Mornington features over 370 retail outlets.

clusters.name: Frankston Gateway
clusters.corridors: Frankston Station (Frankston Line via City Loop) is the major interchange hub. Key roads include Frankston Freeway (M3), Nepean Highway, and Cranbourne Road. Bus routes 781, 784, 785, 791 connect to Langwarrin Plaza and Mount Eliza village.

clusters.name: Baxter-Langwarrin South
clusters.corridors: Bus routes 788, 791 via Cranbourne Road and Nepean Highway connect to Frankston Station. Limited direct rail; primarily bus-dependent area. Langwarrin Plaza accessible via Route 791.

clusters.name: Cranbourne South Growth
clusters.corridors: South Gippsland Highway and Dandenong-Hastings Road corridor. Bus routes via Cranbourne Road connect to Cranbourne Station. Growing residential area with emerging retail precincts.

clusters.name: Devon Meadows Junction
clusters.corridors: South Gippsland Highway and Dandenong-Hastings Road provide major arterial access. Junction Village retail area on South Gippsland Highway corridor. Growing residential area with road-based transport focus.

clusters.name: Frankston North-Seaford
clusters.corridors: Seaford Station (Frankston Line via City Loop) provides direct CBD connection. EastLink toll access at Carrum Downs interchange. Bus routes 760, 780, 901 provide orbital connections via Ballarto Road and Hall Road.

clusters.name: Cranbourne Hub
clusters.corridors: Cranbourne Station (Cranbourne Line via Metro Tunnel) provides direct CBD access. South Gippsland Highway corridor. Bus routes 893, 894, 895. Cranbourne Park shopping precinct is the major retail anchor.

clusters.name: Cranbourne North
clusters.corridors: Bus routes 828, 841, 893, 895 connect to Cranbourne and Narre Warren stations. South Gippsland Highway and Western Port Highway provide major road access. Growing residential corridor with improving transit.

clusters.name: Lynbrook-Hampton Park
clusters.corridors: Lynbrook Station (Cranbourne Line via Metro Tunnel) and Hallam Station (Pakenham Line) provide rail access. South Gippsland Highway and Western Port Highway convergence. Elevated level-crossing-free rail.

clusters.name: Carrum Coastal
clusters.corridors: Carrum, Bonbeach, and Seaford stations (Frankston Line via City Loop) provide beachside rail access. Nepean Highway and coastal connections. Patterson Lakes Lakeview Shopping Centre.

clusters.name: Bangholme-Dandenong South
clusters.corridors: EastLink corridor and Dandenong-Hastings Road provide road access. Mixed industrial-residential character. Bus routes 857, 890, 893 connect to Dandenong precinct.

clusters.name: Chelsea Bayside
clusters.corridors: Chelsea, Edithvale, and Bonbeach stations (Frankston Line via City Loop) rebuilt in 2021 with modern interchanges. Nepean Highway and Wells Road provide arterial access. Strong bayside character.

clusters.name: Narre Warren Central
clusters.corridors: Narre Warren, Hallam, and Berwick stations (Cranbourne/Pakenham Lines via Metro Tunnel) with elevated rail. South Gippsland Highway corridor. Fountain Gate Shopping Centre is the major regional retail anchor.

clusters.name: Dandenong Hub
clusters.corridors: Dandenong Station is a junction where Cranbourne and Pakenham Lines split (via Metro Tunnel). Dandenong-Hastings Road and South Gippsland Highway corridors. Major regional employment hub with EastLink access.

clusters.name: Keysborough-Noble Park
clusters.corridors: Noble Park Station (Cranbourne/Pakenham via Metro Tunnel) provides direct CBD access. Centre Dandenong Road and Springvale Road are primary arteries. Parkmore Shopping Centre is the major retail anchor.

clusters.name: Dingley Village-Springvale
clusters.corridors: Springvale Station (Cranbourne/Pakenham via Metro Tunnel) serves the eastern edge. Springvale Road and Centre Dandenong Road form the main commercial corridors. Sandown Park racecourse nearby.

clusters.name: Noble Park North-Mulgrave
clusters.corridors: Springvale Station (Cranbourne/Pakenham via Metro Tunnel) provides rail access. Springvale Road and Wellington Road are key arteries. Monash University Clayton campus is nearby with bus connections.

clusters.name: Clayton-Clarinda
clusters.corridors: Clayton Station (Cranbourne/Pakenham via Metro Tunnel) is the primary rail access. Clayton Road and Centre Road form commercial corridors. Monash Medical Centre is a major employment anchor.

clusters.name: Aspendale-Mordialloc
clusters.corridors: Aspendale and Mordialloc stations (Frankston Line via City Loop) provide direct CBD rail access. Nepean Highway and Wells Road are primary arteries. Mordialloc village and beachfront provide local retail and recreation.

clusters.name: Parkdale-Mentone
clusters.corridors: Parkdale, Mentone, and Mordialloc stations (Frankston Line via City Loop) provide strong rail connectivity. Nepean Highway and Warrigal Road are primary corridors. Mentone Shopping Centre and village strip anchor the precinct.

clusters.name: Moorabbin-Hampton East
clusters.corridors: Moorabbin and Highett stations (Frankston Line via City Loop) provide rail access. Nepean Highway and Warrigal Road are primary arteries. Moorabbin shopping strip and Centre Road Bentleigh provide retail.

clusters.name: Cheltenham-Beaumaris
clusters.corridors: Cheltenham Station (Frankston Line via City Loop) provides rail access. Nepean Highway and Bay Road are primary arteries. Southland Shopping Centre nearby is the major regional retail hub.

clusters.name: Black Rock-Sandringham
clusters.corridors: Sandringham Station (Sandringham Line terminus) provides direct CBD rail access. Beach Road and Bay Road are primary routes. Sandringham Village shopping precinct and foreshore beaches.

clusters.name: Oakleigh South-Clarinda
clusters.corridors: Oakleigh and Huntingdale stations (Cranbourne/Pakenham via Metro Tunnel) provide rail access. Warrigal Road and Dandenong Road are key corridors. Eaton Mall Oakleigh is the major Greek precinct dining strip.

clusters.name: Geelong CBD
clusters.corridors: V/Line Geelong Station connects direct to Melbourne via the Geelong Line. Moorabool Street, Malop Street, and Ryrie Street form the main retail and commercial precinct. CDC Victoria bus network services the CBD with frequent local routes.

clusters.name: Geelong West
clusters.corridors: Walking distance to V/Line Geelong Station and CBD via Latrobe Terrace. Pakington Street is the main retail strip with boutique shops and cafes. CDC Victoria buses service the precinct.

clusters.name: South Geelong
clusters.corridors: V/Line South Geelong Station provides direct train access to Melbourne. CDC Victoria buses connect the station precinct. Midland Highway and Geelong Ring Road provide road access. Gateway to eastern Geelong suburbs.

clusters.name: Manifold Heights
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria bus routes provide local connections. Midland Highway provides road connectivity to Geelong CBD. Access to Geelong Ring Road for broader regional travel.

clusters.name: Herne Hills
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria bus network connects to surrounding districts. Geelong Ring Road and local roads provide transport access. Mixed residential precinct with local shopping strips.

clusters.name: Belmont & Highton
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service this major residential precinct. Located on the south-western side of Geelong with access to Geelong Ring Road. Highton is a growing commercial centre with retail precincts. Surf Coast Highway provides access to the coast.

clusters.name: Wandana Heights
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria bus routes service the residential precinct. Geelong Ring Road provides major road connectivity. Elevated position with views over Geelong and the bay.

clusters.name: North Geelong
clusters.corridors: V/Line North Geelong Station on the Geelong Line provides commuter rail access. CDC Victoria buses service the district. Waterfront precinct with Rippleside Park providing bay views.

clusters.name: Bell Park & Hamlyn Heights
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria bus network connects to North Geelong Station precinct. Local shopping and community facilities along Separation Street. Access to Geelong Ring Road.

clusters.name: Bell Post Hill
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service the growing precinct. Located on the Geelong Ring Road corridor. Local retail and community amenities along Bacchus Marsh Road.

clusters.name: Norlane & North Shore
clusters.corridors: V/Line North Shore Station on the Geelong Line provides commuter rail access to Melbourne. CDC Victoria buses service the station precinct. Industrial and mixed-use zone with Geelong Ring Road access.

clusters.name: Corio
clusters.corridors: V/Line Corio Station on the Geelong Line provides commuter rail access to Melbourne. CDC Victoria bus network connects the station. Industrial and residential precinct with Geelong Ring Road connectivity.

clusters.name: Leopold-Newcomb
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service the eastern suburbs connecting to Geelong CBD. Bellarine Highway provides road access to the Bellarine Peninsula. Mixed residential with local shopping strips along Bellarine Highway.

clusters.name: Breakwater & St Albans Park
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service the precinct. Geelong Ring Road and local roads provide connectivity. Breakwater is a residential and recreational destination with foreshore access.

clusters.name: Armstrong Creek & Marshall
clusters.corridors: Growing precinct with CDC Victoria bus connections expanding. Road access via Princes Freeway and Geelong Ring Road. Major new residential development area south-west of Geelong with future transport infrastructure planned.

clusters.name: Grovedale
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses connect to surrounding districts. Princes Freeway provides major road access to Melbourne. Torquay Road connects to the Surf Coast. Growing residential and commercial precinct.

clusters.name: Lovely Banks
clusters.corridors: Princes Freeway connects to western Geelong and Melbourne. Local roads and arterials provide connectivity. Residential area with semi-rural character at Geelong's western fringe.

clusters.name: Lara
clusters.corridors: V/Line Lara Station on the Geelong Line provides commuter rail access to Melbourne CBD. Princes Freeway provides direct freeway access. Key gateway between Geelong and Western Melbourne suburbs. Near Avalon Airport.

clusters.name: Avalon & Point Wilson
clusters.corridors: Located west of Lara on Princes Freeway corridor. Bellarine Highway provides alternative road access toward the Bellarine Peninsula. Near Avalon Airport with potential future development.

clusters.name: Barwon Heads
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses connect the southern Bellarine coastal communities. Bellarine Highway is the main road corridor. Barwon Heads village shopping strip and foreshore. Scenic coastal and recreational destination.

clusters.name: Portarlington & East Bellarine
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service the eastern Bellarine coastal strip. Bellarine Highway is the main transport corridor. Portarlington has a ferry to Docklands. Scenic beach towns with local shopping strips.

clusters.name: Upper Bellarine
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses connect the inland Bellarine communities. Bellarine Highway and local roads provide connectivity. Drysdale is the main service centre with local retail.

clusters.name: Ocean Grove
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses service the western Bellarine beach communities. Surf Coast Highway and Bellarine Highway provide road access. Ocean Grove is a major coastal town with retail strips and surf beaches.

clusters.name: Queenscliff & Point Lonsdale
clusters.corridors: CDC Victoria buses connect to Queenscliff regional hub. Bellarine Highway terminus. Queenscliff-Sorrento ferry service connects to the Mornington Peninsula. Historic township with tourism focus.

clusters.name: Werribee South Gateway
clusters.corridors: Bus routes connect to Williams Landing and Laverton stations via Point Cook Road and Princes Freeway. Werribee South is a semi-rural pocket with market gardens and foreshore access.

clusters.name: Werribee Hub
clusters.corridors: Werribee Station (Werribee Line) provides frequent metro services to Melbourne CBD. Wyndham Vale Station serves V/Line regional services. Pacific Werribee is the major regional shopping centre. Princes Freeway provides road access.

clusters.name: Manor Lakes
clusters.corridors: Manor Lakes Station provides rail access via the Wyndham Vale branch. Ballan Road and local roads connect to surrounding areas. Growing residential precinct with emerging local retail.

clusters.name: Williams Landing Hub
clusters.corridors: Williams Landing Station (Werribee Line) provides rapid CBD access. Hoppers Crossing Station via bus connections. Bus interchange with multiple routes. Pacific Werribee and Hoppers Crossing shopping strip accessible via Morris Road.

clusters.name: Point Cook Gateway
clusters.corridors: Bus routes connect to Williams Landing and Laverton stations via Point Cook Road. Local shopping strips along arterial roads. Growing residential area with strong family-oriented character.

clusters.name: Altona Meadows
clusters.corridors: Altona Station (Werribee Line via Altona Loop) provides direct metro access. Pier Street Altona shopping strip with cafes and local retail. Access to Altona Beach and foreshore recreation.

clusters.name: Williams Landing-Truganina
clusters.corridors: Williams Landing Station (Werribee Line) as primary transport hub. Princes Freeway and local roads (Sayers Road, Sneydes Road) connect growing areas. Emerging town centre with new retail.

clusters.name: Altona Foreshore
clusters.corridors: Seaholme and Altona stations (Werribee Line) provide metro access. Pier Street shopping and beachside recreation. Local bus connections to Williamstown.

clusters.name: Laverton Hub
clusters.corridors: Laverton and Aircraft stations (Werribee Line) provide metro connectivity. Aviation Road shopping and facilities. Princes Freeway access. Regional logistics and industrial hub in Laverton North.

clusters.name: Rockbank West
clusters.corridors: Rockbank Station provides V/Line regional rail access via Ballarat and Geelong lines. Western Freeway provides regional road corridor. Growing residential area with semi-rural character transitioning to suburban.

clusters.name: Aintree Growth
clusters.corridors: Bus routes connect to Rockbank Station and regional network. Western Freeway corridor. Growing residential area with emerging local centres and new community infrastructure.

clusters.name: Deer Park-Derrimut
clusters.corridors: Deer Park Station (Sunbury Line via Metro Tunnel) provides metro and V/Line interchange. Western Ring Road and Derrimut Road form the logistics corridor. Derrimut Village Shopping Centre.

clusters.name: Sunshine West-Albion
clusters.corridors: Sunshine Station (Sunbury Line via Metro Tunnel) with V/Line connections to Bendigo and Ballarat. Albion and Ardeer stations also on the Sunbury Line. Sunshine Plaza and Sunshine Marketplace shopping centres. Hampshire Road retail strip.
